# Coding Preferences

- Always prefer simple solutions
- Avoid duplicating code — check for existing similar functionality elsewhere in the codebase before writing new code
- Write code that accounts for different environments: dev, test, and prod
- Only make changes that are explicitly requested or are clearly related to the requested change
- When fixing a bug, exhaust all options using the existing implementation before introducing a new pattern or technology. If a new approach is introduced, remove the old implementation to avoid duplicate logic
- Keep the codebase clean and organized
- Avoid writing one-off scripts inside source files; keep them separate if needed
- Refactor any file that exceeds 200–300 lines of code
- Mock data is for tests only — never use mock or stub data in dev or prod environments
- Never overwrite the `.env` file without first asking and receiving explicit confirmation
